column168: A BOX WAS ON A CONVEYER BELT IN SECONDARY 22 WHEN IT WAS OBSERVED ON FIRE. TWO FEDEX EMPLOYEES USED FIRE EXTINGUISHERS TO PUT THE FIRE OUT. THE BOX WAS COMPLETELY DENIGRATED AS A RESULT OF THE FIRE, THE CONTENTS THAT WEREN'T BURNED BEYOND RECOGNITION INCLUDE TWO PLASTIC BOTTLES OF WHAT IS BELIEVED TO BE ACETONE, AND FOUR PRINTER INK CARTRIDGES. A SECOND BOX, POSSIBLY FROM AMAZON WAS BADLY DAMAGED BY THE FIRE. THAT BOX HAS THE AMAZON LOGO AND TAPE ON IT. IT IS UNKNOWN IF THE BOX WAS REUSED BY THE SHIPPER OR IF IT WAS AN ACTUAL AMAZON SHIPMENT. THE BOX CONTAINED 20 AMAZON BASIC ALKALINE BATTERIES AA SIZE, 8 AMAZON BASIC AAA ALKALINE BATTERIES AND SEVERAL MOUSETRAPS. A THIRD BOX SUSTAINED DAMAGE BUT THE CONTENT: OVERHEAD CAMERAS WERE INTACT, THE THIRD SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED BY THE FORD MOTOR CO. THE REMAINS OF ALL THREE PACKAGES ARE BEING HELD FOR AN FAA INSPECTION. MEM SECFO HAZMAT MANAGER STAN SATCHELL AS WELL AS FEDEX FAA PHIS STEVEN REDECKER & RYAN POHLKE WERE PREVIOUSLY NOTIFIED.

column25: GOCCE DI BYRON DI RUSSO DAVIDE
column168: The shipper offered three boxes. we found one box was emitting a strong odor. Upon opening that box we found two more boxes. We opened each of the two inner boxes to find a plastic bag filled with 10mL glass vials that were heaped into the plastic bag. There was no separation of the vials or absorbent material. In the third box we found 15 inner boxes inside a plastic bag that contain 50mL glass bottles of perfume. The UN4G outermost boxes appear to have been reused so it is questionable if the current inner packagings were tested with their UN POP boxes. The freight was held pending an FAA inspection. MEM SECFO Hazmat Manager Stan Satchell was notified electronically.
column169: No comments provided

column168: On December 4, 2018, the FRA Hazmat Inspectors were in our Brewster Yard doing a routine  inspection when they came across car HOMX 101241 leaking from the Liquid Valve plug on the A end. I, John Vergis Environmental Officer for the WLE, was called to investigate this leak.  When I looked at the car, I noticed that the valve was leaking through the valve plug.  I checked to see if the valve  handle was loose and it was.  I tightened the valve handle and the leak stopped.  I checked the valve  plug to see if it was tight and it was.  It needed new thread tape.  The plug was bottomed out in the valve.  The FRA Inspector removed original seal named TARGA from the protective housing lid.   They installed seal number DOT FRA 52040.  I removed this seal to make a repair and then installed seal number 971763.  I then returned the car to service.  NARRI: 5(4+5)x2=47                                      Cause Code:115 , 282
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

At 0216 ERTS was contacted by Alex Belew of XPO Logistics XSL about a cargo release. It was reported  that due to a cylinder valve release an unknown amount of UN1016, 2.3, 2.1 Compressed Carbon  Monoxide released from at least 1 100 pound cylinder. The caller stated that the released product  was contained to the trailer. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and it was determined a  contractor needed to be sent. ERTS dispatched Environmental Management Alternatives to assess  and clean the release. Contactors arrive on site and reported that the cylinders are encased in a  unit with hoses connecting each cylinder in a loop system. One of the hoses was observed to not be  connected to anything and could have released the material. It is unconfirmed what cylinder had  the release. There was no hissing or observation of a release at the time of entry into the trailer.  EMA personnel have a 4-gas meter on site to get accurate safe readings and determine the  trailer is safe for continued transport. They watched 4-gas meter closely for 10 minutes, none of  the cylinders showed any signs that they had released.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

column168: On 12/1/2018 at 0217 ET Jesse with XPO terminal LSL contacted ERTS concerning a spill of 2-3 cups UN1263 paint from (1) 500-gallon metal tote cap. The spill is thought to be a result of a broken gasket on the tote. Due to the need for a possible gasket replacement, ERTS dispatched USES Environmental to go observe the release. USES personnel will determine whether or not the gasket is cause of the release. Per the State of LA regulations, ERTS contacted the LA DPS, Ojunnaike took receipt of the call and provided report number 18-06009 to the incident. ERTS generated LA DEQ online report number OK1Q 5009. ERTS attempted to contact the Caddo Parish LEPC, A voicemail was left detailing the incident. Chemtrec contacted report number: 2018120100019. A DOT5800 will be required due to the size of the container. No drains, soils, or waterways have been impacted by the release. Contractor arrived on site and stated the spill was due to a bad gasket. Shipper went to the seen on 12/4 and replaced the gasket.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: At 1222 ET, ERTS was notified by John Lamothe of XPO (XEE) regarding a cargo release. According to the caller, approximately 2-gallons of UN2794 "Batteries, wet, filled", 8 released to a trailer floor (465-6002) from (2) 1,500-lb. metal containers due to being tipped over when it arrived at the customer's facility at 647 Summers Street in Boston, MA. The caller indicated the release was contained to the trailer floor. Due to the incident occurring at the customer location and not at the terminal, ERTS dispatched Clean Harbors out of Boston, MA with an unknown ETA at this time. Clean Harbors could not respond to the spill response, therefore, Moran Environmental was notified. Moran Environmental, Global Remediation nor New England Disposal Technologies could respond to the spill due to teams being out from the office. ERTS notified Environmental Restoration who indicated they will let ERTS know if they can clean the release. Environmental Restoration indicated they did not have personnel to clean the release. Allstate Power-Vac was notified of the release, and provided an ETA of 1700 to clean the release. ERTS notified DEP on-site, initial caller and driver of the ETA. There were no drains or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. The Massachusetts DEP was notified, however, due to the release not meeting MASS DEP limits, the release is not reportable. The local fire department was also made aware of the release and is responding to the incident. There is a DOT 5800 required for this release due to its size. Chemtrec was notified and Spencer issued report #20181210-00137. ERTS will upload the BOL and SDS.

column168: On 12/3/18, a Veolia driver picked up the tote of hazardous waste from the offeror at the offeror's  location. The Veolia driver continued to their next stop in Manchester, New Hampshire. Along the way,  the driver had to make a quick and hard turning maneuver to avoid a fire truck in downtown,  Manchester. The driver was concerned about the tote of material after the maneuver and pulled over  to check the tote. Upon opening the back door of the truck, a small amount of liquid came out of the  back of the truck. The driver then moved the truck to a flat area as they were on a slight incline. The  driver then called the Veolia home office to report the spill and request assistance. The driver also  walked the area from discovery of the spill to the area of the maneuver and saw a small amount of  liquid on the street. The leaked material did not get on any third party vehicles and did not enter any  storm drains. Duration of the release was about two minutes. Less than 3 gallons of material was  released to the outside of the vehicle. This was cleaned up by Veolia employees or evaporated prior to cleanup. About 32 gallons of leaked material remained within the vehicle. The 32 estimated gallons  that came out of container that did not escape the vehicle was cleaned up by in-house Veolia  employees. Approximately half of the free liquids released from the tote was absorbed by cardboard  that was in the vehicle. Additionally about 10-15 gallons of liquid was in the back of the truck that  needed to be collected and cleaned up. Location of the tear on the IBC was about three quarters of  the way up the side of the tote. The tote was extremely old and had not been filled completely. The  offeror told Veolia employees that it had taken them a long time to fill it to the point it was and that  they did not want to continue filling the container. Upon inspection it was discovered that the side  walls of the container were extremely pliable and had evidence of degrading. The tear appears to  have been caused by the degraded plastic contacting the surrounding metal cage of the tote during the vehicle's swift maneuver while in transit.  Once the shipment arrived at the Veolia facility, the  remaining material was transferred into an appropriate UN specification IBC prior to continuing  transport to the disposal facility.
column169: The primary cause of the leak appears to be the age of the container that was used. The tear in the  container occurred during an emergency maneuver around a fire truck in a downtown location. The  driver did a good job checking the load after the maneuver and we will stress this procedure with other  drivers. In the future we will also inquire about the age of containers when we obtain  information from the offeror that it has taken some time to fill a container.

column168: At 1159 ET, Clay Christian driver of truck #6322150 called to report a release. Caller stated that upon arrival to customer location 5 metal totes were refused by customer due to visible leakage from the top side lids. Contractor arrived on site and confirmed arrived onsite and confirmed that 2 cups of UN1992, 3, III, Entegrate IC 3716 released from (5) 330 gallon metal totes. The totes were wiped down and the caps were tightened. All waste material from the event was containerized to a 15 gallon metal drum. The totes were refused again by the consignee, so another contractor was dispatched by ERTS to handle the remainder of the incident. Contractor arrived onsite and determined that the cap gaskets were defective. Contractor removed, cleaned, and re-secured the faulty gaskets. Contractor performed a slosh test to be sure the totes were operating correctly. All tests were successful and the totes were sent on to the consignee. A couple impacted pads were added to the waste container that was generated by the previous contractor. There were no soils, waterways, or storm drains impacted by the release. There is no further clean up needed.

column168: At 1630 ET, ERTS was notified by XPO (XHG) regarding a cargo release. According to the caller, approximately 1 gal of "Axalta Paint Lacquer" released to a trailer floor (HFAD2296) from a (1) 5 gallon metal pale due to a forklift puncture. The caller indicated the release was contained to the trailer floor. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined the release would need to have a contractor dispatched because of the client does not have enough recovery drums. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. Hepaco responded to this incident and used oil dry on the impacted areas. 1-5gal poly pail was placed into a 55gal metal drum along with the spent absorbents. All waste was left on site for disposal.

column169: WHEN HANDLING HAZMATS, LOADERS AND UNLOADERS SHOULD BE CAREFUL NOT TO DROP PACKAGES. column168: Veolia personnel reported to Chemtrec, tank car TILX100830 may be leaking based on evidence at their loading facility.  Chemtrec in turn notified Norfolk Southern.  Upon inspection by a contractor, TILX100830 was found to be leaking from the liquid line.  The leak was the result of a securement chain preventing the liquid line closure cap from tightening down completely. The leak was stopped and the closure cap was properly installed.  The securement chain on the liquid line cap was found to be non-compliant with regulations.  The car is being held pending the shipper sending a certified MRU to repair the problem.

column168: Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVR) inside the package. The 90 day beacon on the CVR contains 1.75g lithium metal content so this was a lithium metal battery packaged in equipment shipment. Package had no markings that it was a dangerous goods/hazardous materials shipment. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and delivered the unit to our repair department. We notified the shipper they shipped a dangerous good without the proper labels and documentation and that they needed to remedy this in the future and that Universal Avionics was required to report the incident. There was no release.
column169: Our personnel have received training on recognizing hazardous materials arriving at our dock with issues and to notify management when an incident occurs. We provided additional training to recognize when a hazardous material arrives without the appropriate markings or documentation and no release and to immediately report it to management so we can capture all the appropriate information in order to report the incident. We have also notified customers and dealers through newsletters, a notice on our customer website and a service bulletin about reshipping this particular product for repairs and the need to ship as dangerous goods/hazardous material.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 12/17/2018 at 1609 hours EST personnel in the Boyles Yard, Birmingham, AL discovered GATX31821, a loaded tank car of Waste Flammable Liquids, N.O.S. (Toluene, Xylene) with a release coming from the pressure relief valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, Geocycle, was notified. MEI, a CSXT response contractor, responded and found the pressure relief valve activated and venting. The issues were identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Geocycle to George Colvin (662-549-2860).  The shipper George confirmed that they had an issue with one of their holding tanks used to load this car at their plant and found that an unknown additive in the product was causing a chemical reaction to occur.  MEI was forced to vent and relieve the pressure on the car.  The car is being placed on hold pending further assistance and analytical on the product to be completed by the shipper.    NAR Cause Code: 422 – Reclosing pressure relief valve OTHER  5(5+3+1) x (2+4) = 270 NARRI   Birmingham, AL – 12/17/18 –GATX31821-Waste Flammable Liquids, N.O.S. (Toluene, Xylene)

column168: Inbound crew reported strong, pungent smell like a spilled/spoiled milk emanating from the main deck  into the galley and cockpit. Upon investigation, smell was coming from pallet in A2 position but no  apparent damage to the pallet or its contents and no leakage or residue on the Aircraft floor or around  the pallet. Pallet was offloaded and the smell dissipated from the cabin; pallet is the absolute cause of the smell as it is even apparent on the ramp. Different classes of HAZMAT were on that same pallet (Class 2.1, 3, 8)  After taking the pallet apart found that 3 out of 20 boxes containing UN1201 begun to leak and emit a nocuous odor, no other were compromised.  3 boxes total were separated from the others as they were damaged or leaking from the cap The boxes were proper and the plastic Jerri cans are UN stamped but it seems that the caps were not sealed good and leaked.

ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and determined the release could be cleaned with a sweeper and PPE, and containerized into a (1) 30-gallon metal drum. The tote was requested to remain at the terminal due to the cap being opened. After caller removed product from the trailer, ERTS notified Chemtrec, which notified the shipper. The shipper indicated the product may react under high energy, but a nitrogen blanket is not necessary as the inert gas to fill the tote. The shipper also noted the product did not use a nitrogen blanket , and the terminal personnel just needed to ensure the valve was closed, then shipment could continue. Terminal personnel did secure the valve to ensure the product could continue to consignee. There were no drains, soils or waterways reported to have been impacted by the release. column168: Cargo Tank was in the process of being unloaded at the customer location which is a chemical plant. About 40 minutes into the unloading process the plant personnel noticed a leak from the rear of the tank. It was determined that sump gasket had failed resulting in a leak of product around the gasket. Upon investigation it was determined that the gasket was made out of a material that is incompatible with nitric acid. The spill was contained in the containment area at the plant unloading site. Plant personnel responded and cleaned up the spill.
column169: Review tanker preparation procedures and make necessary changes to prevent recurrence.

column168: A Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. driver was in the process of performing a Pretrip inspection after receiving a shipment. The driver noticed a small leak from the rear hatch of his trailer. The driver immediately donned the proper personal protective equipment, applied absorbent material to stop any further spillage, and notified facility personnel and local dispatch. A third party subcontracted response crew responded to the scene, donned the proper PPE and remediated the impacted areas of the trailer and ground below the trailer. The waste generated during the cleanup process was properly containerized for future disposal. The rear hatch of the trailer was properly tightened and the tanker was put back into service.
column169: Prior to the time the tanker was loaded for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. An investigation into the root cause determined that one bolt on the rear hatch of the trailer was loose after the trailer went for a certified wash out at a wash facility. To mitigate future occurrences, management has implemented and trained drivers on a checklist which is to be used after receiving any tank trailer from a wash facility, and before the trailer is dispatched on any subsequent trips. After properly tightening the loose bolt, the tanker was returned to service.

column168: During routine facility offload operations, several non bulk containers were identified as having been improperly closed to manufacturers specification, thus resulting in release. In appropriate personal protective equipment, the facility supervisor was successful in properly closing and in over packing the non bulk containers for shipment to final destination. The impact of this release was contained to the transport trailer floor with no impact to land, soil, water water ways or storm drains. The transport trailer floor was thoroughly cleaned as well.
column169: The generator was notified of the release and improper closure of the containers and advised of manufacturer closure specifications and generator responsibility to prepare containers for transport. The driver who accepted these containers into transportation separated from the role of transport driver.

column168: The pallet was loaded onto the aircraft. During the loading process the loadmaster assigned to the aircraft noticed an odor emitting from the  pallet. The dangerous goods response team was called to the aircraft to investigate the pallet. Upon inspection, no leaks were observed. The loadmaster instructed the pallet to be removed from the aircraft to undergo a full breakdown to find the cause of the odor. Once the pallet was back inside the warehouse the covering and plastic wrap was removed from skid. Upon removing the plastic wrap one jerrican of UN3267 Corrosive Liquid, Basic, Organic, N.O.S was found to be leaking. The clean up vendor was called to clean up and repackage the the skid. During the cleanup process it was discovered that the jerricans were not properly labeled.  The shipment was presented as an overpack. However, the jerricans on the inside of the overpack were not correctly labeled by the shipper as they were missing the required Cargo Aircraft Only label. The Cargo Aircraft Only label was reproduced on the outside of the overpack but not on the individual jerricans inside the overpack.
Driver was conducting loading procedures, but did not follow proper procedure/routine. Driver did not check to make sure valves were closed before disconnecting hose.
column169: Drivers will be retrained on loading and unloading procedures with an emphasis on checking valves before connecting/disconnecting hoses.

THE PERSON SCANNING IRREGS NEAR DOOR 216 NOTICED A LEAKING HAZMAT ON THE IRREG BELT. HE STOPPED THE BELT NOTIFIED THE NEAREST SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. BECAUSE THE PACKAGE WAS CORROSIVE, I ALTERED MY PPE TO INCLUDE THE SILVER SHIELD INNER LINERS. I CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. I USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID. THEN ADDED CLAY ABSORBENT TO SOLIDIFY ANY REMAINING LIQUID. I SWEPT UP CONTAMINATED MATERIALS   PUT IT INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY. I THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE THE 3, IT LEAKED ON TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I FOUND THAT ONE OF THE CAPS HAD COME OFF THAT THE 3 REMAINING BOTTLES WERE SOILED BY THE PRODUCT.

column168: On December 19, 2018, at 0641 hours personnel in the CSXT Louisville, KY yard reported a strong odor in the area of tank car GATX 8194, a tank car loaded Sulfur.  The car was isolated and the shipper’s emergency contact, Phillips 66, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2018-1219-00044.  Environmental Management Specialists (EMS), a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and confirmed the car was leaking vapors from the pressure relief vent assembly.  The issue’s identified and corrective actions were communicated to shipper’s representative- Josh Morgenroth.  Contractor personnel replaced the rupture disc, which appeared to be worn and preventing adequate sealing of the assembly, and the release was secured.  The car was released for transportation.
column169: (NAR Cause Code: 439 corroded disk, not ruptured)

column168: Personnel reported that the tank car was leaking from the bottom of the tank car.  Responders arrived and found that the bottom outlet valve was malfunctioning and the bottom outlet cap was less than tool tight.

On December 19, 2018 at approximately 15:00 a car inspector at Consolidated Rail Morrisville, Pennsylvania  Yard, reported that NATX 280089, a loaded tank car of UN 2303, Isopropenylbenzene was leaking from the  bottom of the tank car. The tank car was isolated and the Shipper, Advansix was directly notified. Hepaco, a  Conrail response Contractor and Joe Caccamo, Conrail Manager of Hazardous Material was dispatched to respond.   Upon inspection it was identified that the leak was originating from the valve stem on the bottom outlet valve and  no repair would be able to make to secure the tank car. A secondary containment pan was placed beneath the bottom  outlet valve with chemical pads to contain any additional leakage. The Shipper, Advansix, Daniel Sekel (215) 807-8445 was updated on the situation and informed a field transfer was necessary. He identified NATX 280024 as a suitable  receiving tank car for the transfer.   The product was transferred into NATX 280024 without incident. Currently NATX 280089 is on hold at the yard pending  FRA Movement approval to home shop for repairs.      NARRI: 2(5+3+0) X (2+0) = 32 Cause Code" 707

Tank Car GATX 1880 reported leaking from Manway of car. Inspection found 2 of 8 Manway Swingbolts less than tool tight. Manway Swingbolts were tightened and car returned to transportation. Released  product was decontaminated from the side of the car and wipes were placed in a drum for disposal by shipper.

column169: THIS HAZMAT PACKAGE WAS LEAKING A BLUE COLORED LIQUID LEAKING OVER THE TOP OF BOX, THROUGH ONE TOP CORNER AND UPPER SIDE PORTION OF BOX. THIS IS INDICATIVE OF LEAKAGE FROM WITHIN AND THAT EXTRA CAUTION SHOULD/MUST BE EXERCISED. ESPECIALLY WHEN DEALING WITH KNOWN HAZMATS, IT IS IMPERATIVE THAT IT SHOULD NOT LEAVE THE TRAILER IF IT IS INDEED COMPROMISED. THE AUDITOR'S PORTION OF THE SHIPPING PAPERS WERE AFFECTED BY THE CORROSIVE CONTENTS. PLEASE ENSURE THAT ANY STRANGE LOOKING COLOR ON A HAZMAT BOX THAT DISCOLORS LABELS AND THE BOX ITSELF MUST ALERT EMPLOYEE TO STOP FURTHER PROGRESSION TO ENSURE PACKAGE IS INDEED SAFE TO PROCEED.

column168: On 12/30/18 at 1053 hours  the train dispatcher, advised Train Q69229 reported four cars derailed at MP Z 196.2 on the Blue Ridge Subdivision, Florence Division.  This is located near Peppers Creek Rd/SR 1566 in Ashford, North Carolina.  Two Ammonium Nitrate cars derailed and rolled down a hill.  Local emergency crews were notified and the shipper was notified via Chemtrec (2018-1230-00026) .  In addition the state Department of Environment and Natural Resources was notified (115862).  Marion Environmental , a CSX contractor was dispatched to the scene.  They were able to contain the spilled material and later used vacuum trucks to remove the spilled product and the product that remained inside of the railcars.  The cars were then removed from the scene.  All recovered material was taken to a staging location and will be transported to a facility for disposal.

column168: Driver was on ramp for I-85 N/I-73S when vehicle hit black ice on bridge caused by snow bank on upper side of bridge left from plowing efforts melting and running across roadway. When the driver hit the ice, the trailer started sliding to the left following the grade of the bridge. Driver tried to gain control, but lost control, causing rollover and fire. Trailer sustained heavy damage, but is impossible to determined what exactly failed because of the extensive damage and total loss as a result of the fire.  The duration of the release was less than 1 hour, as the product burned. Because of the position on the bridge, the product that escaped through the bridge drains went one direction, and product that ran down the side of the roadway went another, causing cleanup in two different storm drainage areas.  Fire crews responded and put the fire out, then environmental crews hired by Associated Petroleum cleaned up the remaining contamination. Testing was conducted to see if there was any effects on local soil and groundwater from the product and firefighting foam used in the incident. Results haven't been completed to this date.
column169: This event should not have occurred. Roadways were dry and the driver had no reason to expect ice on the bridge. There was a large snowbank on the upper side of the roadway that should have been cleared away after a snowstorm that move through 3 days earlier. There should be a standard created where DOT agencies, while clearing snow, move the snow and ice to the low side of the bridge instead of cutting a path through it for traffic to pass. It is our opinion that this accident was completely avoidable by clearing the snow to the low side so that when it melts, it goes into the drain instead of across the road only to re-freeze at night.

column168: The customer tank had a 905 gallon capacity.  It had 500 in it.  He had 597 gallons to offload and it wouldn't all fit.  Our stance is to offload to the 90% mark.  He called in for his safety check call and the caller told him to offload 315 gallons and shut down.  Because of the little amount it would only take 1-2 minutes to offload that amount but because it was flammable he would have to use his pump.  He advised he didn't feel safe doing this due to the short duration and trying to figure out how to clear his lines afterwards.  He was asked to do it anyways and after a few minutes the tank started overflowing.
column169: The driver should have refused to unload at this point since he already wasn't feeling comfortable. In addition those who do the checklists with the driver were coached on this as well.  Partial unloads using a pump versus air pressure make this a higher risk situation

column168: At approximately 23:59 CT on 12/8/18, the WFRX 836161 suffered damaged to one of three bottom hopper doors resulting in the release of approximately 48,000 pounds of material to the track bed.  The damaged was incurred as a result of a broken drawbar from a car that was three cars ahead of this car.  The debris from the drawbar failure tore the bottom door.  Furnace ash was spread over approximately 1/4 mile of track as the train was coming to a stop.  Responders assessed the site and a tackifier was applied over the heaviest concentrations of dust to prevent further dispersion by wind.  A vacuum truck was utilized to removed impacted ballast and remaining dust on the track bed.  The damaged car was moved to Cutbank, MT for repair of the door and balancing of the load with lime.  Once balanced, the car continued in transportation to the consignee.  The volume estimated to have been released is estimated based upon visual observation of remaining material in the bin.

column168: UNLOADERS EITHER MOVED A LEAKING HAZMAT OR PLACED THE HAZMAT ON ITS SIDE, IGNORING ORIENTATION ARROWS AND CAUSED THE PACKAGE TO LEAK. NO OTHER BOXES WERE DAMAGED, SO THIS LOOKS LIKE A NEW LEAK. THEY THEN PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD THE ENTIRE LONG TRAILER WITHOUT INFORMING THEIR SUPERVISOR IN SPITE OF THE NOXIOUS ODOR. SUPERVISOR DISCOVERED BOX WHEN THE TRAILER WAS EMPTY AND CALLED DMP. RESPONDER ARRIVED AT DOOR 38 WEARING ALL PPE. USING THE DECISION TREE AND MARKINGS ON THE PACKAGE THE INCIDENT WAS HANDLED ACCORDINGLY AND THE PACKAGE WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO DMP.

THE OUTBOUND SUPERVISOR NOTICED A WET HAZMAT PACKAGE ON HIS BELT BY HIS LVD ND IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE PROCESS OF THE PACKAGE AND CONTACTED A DESIGNATED RESPONDER. THE RESPONDER PROPERLY PROCURED THE PACKAGE AND TRANSPORTED IT QUALITY CONTROL FOR PROCESSING.

column168: ARRIVED WITH PPE ON TO FIND HAZMAT ON FLOOR SITTING UPRIGHT. USED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE TO CONTAINERIZE AND CLEAN UP SPILL. RETURNED TO DMP AREA FOR PROCESSING. ON OPENING PACKAGE FOUND TWO OF THE BOTTLES HAD CRACKS NEAR THE CAP LIKE THEY HAD BEEN SQUASHED, BUT NO INDICATION FROM THE PACKAGE THAT THIS HAD HAPPENED.

RESPONDER DISCOVERED LEAKING PACKAGE ON A PACKAGE CAR BOX LINE. PACKAGE WAS A LOCAL PICKUP; HAZMAT WAS NOT AUDITED AT TIME OF PICKUP. PACKAGE BROUGHT BACK TO PSC WHERE ALL CONTENTS WERE DISPOSED OF THROUGH DMP.

PACKAGE WAS CLEARLY LABELED AS A HAZMAT WITH ORIENTATION ARROWS. PACKAGE WAS LOADED ON IT'S SIDE ABOVE THE THIRD SHELF OF BOXES AT LEAST 4 FEET HIGH IN THE TRAILER WITH HEAVIER PACKAGE ON TOP OF IT. UNLOADER DISCOVERED THE LEAK WHILE UNLOADING THE LAST WALL IN THE TRAILER AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. SUPERVISOR SECURED THE SCENE AND NOTIFIED DMP. RESPONDER ARRIVED WEARING FULL PPE, ADDING SILVER SHIELD GLOVES FOR THE CORROSIVE, AND USING PROPER PROCEDURES REMOVED THE LEAKER AND OTHER PACKAGES AND TRANSPORTED THEM BACK TO DMP FOR PROCESSING.
column169: RETRAINING ON PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES FOR HAZMATS.

column17: ROSS FOGG FUEL OIL CO INC
column168: INITIAL INCIDENT: ON DECEMBER 5, 2018, A TANK TRAILER OPERATED BY ROSS ENTERPRISES TRUCKING ROLLED-OVER AT MILE 54.6 ON SOUTHBOUND RT. 55, CAUSING A SPILL OF #2 HEATING OIL, E #1) THE TRUCKING COMPANY IMMEDIATELY TOOK RESPONSIBILITY AND HIRED CLEANUP CONTRACTORS TO REMEDIATE THE SPILL. THE TANKER WAS HAULING 7,600 GALLONS OF PRODUCT, OF WHICH 4,213 GALLONS WAS RECOVERED AS LIQUID PRODUCT BY CLEANUP CREWS. OF THE 3,387 GALLONS OF REMAINING PRODUCT SPILLED, SOME WAS RECOVERED USING ABSORBENT SPILL CLEANUP MATERIALS, SOME SOAKED INTO SOILS ON THE ROADSIDE, AND SOME GOT INTO A STORM DRAIN HIDDEN BY SOIL AND DEBRIS, (IMAGE #2) THE ACTUAL AMOUNTS IN EACH OF THOSE CANNOT BE DETERMINED. THE STORM DRAIN OUTFALLS TO THE MANTUA CREEK.  AREA OF IMPACT THE RT. 55 ROAD SURFACE, SEVERAL HUNDRED FEET OF SHOULDER SOIL AND THE STORM DRAIN WERE INITIALLY AFFECTED. THE PRODUCT THAT ENTERED THE STORM DRAIN WAS DISCHARGED TO THE MANTUA CREEK DOWNGRADIENT OF THE ACCIDENT SCENE. APPROXIMATELY 4 MILES OF CREEK WAS AFFECTED, WITH PRODUCT ACCUMULATING IN POCKET ALONG THE DEBRIS-CLOGGED WASTER-COURSE.  WHAT SPECIFICALLY WAS DONE TO CLEAN UP  THE CLEANUP BEGAN IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE ACCIDENT, WITH LOCAL RESPONDERS MAKING EFFORTS TO CONTAIN THE SPILL USING DIRT DIKES AND TRENCHING. THE CONTRACTORS HIRED BY THE RESPONSIBILITY PARTY REMOVED ALL ACCESSIBLE LIQUID PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER AND DRAINAGE DITCH USING VACUUM TRUCKS. OIL ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE APPLIED TO TRENCHES CREATED TO COLLECT THE SPILL. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND REMOVED FROM THE ROAD SHOULDER THE FOLLOWING MORNING. WHEN IT WAS DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT HAD ENTERED THE CREEK, THE SCOPE OF THE OPERATION SHIFTED, AND CREWS WERE DISPATCHED TO DEPLOY BOTH CONTAINMENT AND ABSORBENT BOOM AT SEVERAL LOCATIONS ALONG THE CREEK. THE POCKETS OF PRODUCT ARE WERE REMOVED USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND VACUUM TRUCKS. MANY PARTS OF THE CREEK ARE HARD TO ACCESS AND CLOGGED WITH DEBRIS, WHICH CREATES A CHALLENGE TO THE OPERATION. IN ADDITION TO THE CLEANUP CONTRACTORS, THE RESPONSIBLE PARTY, AT THE HARD TO ACCESS AND CLOGGED WITH DEBRIS, WHICH CREATES A CHALLENGE TO THE OPERATION. IN ADDITION TO THE CLEANUP CONTRACTORS, THE RESPONSIBLE PARTY, AT THE DIRECTION OF DEP, RETAINED AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTING FIRM AND LICENSED SITE REMEDIATION PROFESSIONAL (LSRP), BRINKERHOFF ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES. A PROFESSIONAL WILDLIFE RECOVERY/ASSESSMENT FIRM, TRI-STATE BIRD RESCUE, WAS CONTRACTED TO ASSESS IMPACTS TO WILDLIFE AND RECOVER/REHABILITATE AFFECTED SPECIES. THE NEW JERSEY DIVISION OF FISH & WILDLIFE AND THE FEDERAL FISH & WILDLIFE SERVICE HAVE ALSO BEEN MADE AWARE OF THE SITUATION.

column168: ON MONDAY, 12/10/2018 AT APPROXIMATELY 2120 HRS, DRIVER DAN TUCKER WAS STOPPED IN HIS TRACTOR WITH 53' DAY VAN CHECKING HIS TRAILER PRIOR TO DEPARTING. HE WAS FACING SOUTH IN THE WEST LOT OF THE BROWN TERMINAL AT 3536 NICHOLSON AVE, KANSAS CITY MISSOURI, 64120. HE NOTICED A CLEAR LIQUID LEAKING OUT OF THE TRAILER DOOR AND IMMEDIATELY CAME INTO THE OFFICE TO NOTIFY THE SUPERVISOR, WILMELLONE. DAN AND I WENT OUTSIDE AND DETERMINED THAT THIS WAS A POTENTIAL HAZMAT SPILL. DAN BACKED THE TRUCK OFF OFF OF THE PAVED PORTION OF THE LOT AND ONTO THE GRAVEL PORTION TO PREVENT THE LIQUID FROM POSSIBLY GOING DOWN THE STORM DRAIN. I IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE KANSAS CITY, MO FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THEN RESPONDED WITHIN IN MINUTES. THEN CONTAINED THE SPILL SEALED THE LEAKING TOTE AND SECURED THE SCENE PRIOR TO LEAVING. ONE OF THE TWO TOTES ON DAN'S TRAILER WAS DETERMINED TO HAVE SUFFERED A SMALL CRACK APPROXIMATELY 10" FROM THE BOTTOM ON THE SIDE FACING THE RIGHT WALL OF THE TRAILER. THIS POSSIBLY OCCURRED DURING LOADING. DAN COMPLAINED OF SOME DIFFICULTY. HE WAS TRANSPORTED TO NKC HOSPITAL BY AMBULANCE TREATED AND RELEASED.

column168: PKG SIGNED OFF BY AA IN 8411 ON 12/18, YET THIS PKG DID NOT RECEIVE A PAL LABEL UNTIL 12/27. LOADED ON PKG CAR, DRIVER NOTICED SMALL BLACK GRAINS COMING FROM BOX AND PLACED IN DRIVER RELEASE BAGS. UPON RETURNING TO CENTER IN PM DRIVER LEFT PKG WITH AA ON LOCAL SORT WHO PUT IN HOLDING AREA. BECAUSE OF HOLIDAY PERIOD THE PKG WAS NOT SENT TO THE DMP FOR PROCESSING UNTIL AFTER NEW YEARS. RESPONDER DISCOVERED PKG IN DMP ON 1/4 AS IT WAS NOT THERE THE PRIOR DAY. RESPONDER IN FULL PPE   NEW DECISION TREE PROCESSED PKG USING FLAMMABLE SOLIDS RESPONSE SHEET. RESPONDER CAREFULLY CLEANED UP THE SPILLED BLACK GRAINS INSIDE THE RELEASE BAG AND BOX. UPON INSPECTION THE RESPONDER OBSERVED THAT 1 OF 3 CONTAINERS HAD A CRACKED CAP THAT COULD NOT BE SCREWED BACK ON PLASTIC BOTTLE. ALL CONTENTS WERE SWEPT UP AND PLACED INTO GREEN DMP BAG SEALED WITH TAPE AND PLACED ON DMP SHELF

column25: TRADEBE TREATMENT AND RECYCLING OF TENNESSEE, LLC
column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. On December 19, 2018 the Tradebe Transportation, LLC driver inadvertently hooked up to the wrong 40-foot dump trailer. The trailer was transported to Covanta, a non-hazardous disposal facility in Huntsville, Alabama and dumped. Covanta personnel removed the material from the disposal pit and staged on a concrete/asphalt floor at the facility.  On December 19 at approximately 11 :30AM Tradebe notified Covanta that the trailer we were delivering to their location was not the correct trailer and that it had hazardous waste on it. We inquired if the load had been delivered yet and were told that it had. We requested that they identify the materials location and immediately isolate the load as it had hazardous waste in it. Tradebe then notified its driver to turn around and head back to Covanta so Tradebe could retrieve the material delivered. Tradebe immediately began searching for a response group to assist in retrieval of the material and found Environmental Products & Services of Vermont, Inc. (EPSVT). They were dispatched to assist in retrieving, reloading, and transporting the material back to Tradebe in Millington, TN. The removal of material began on 12/20 and ended on 12/21 with all roll-off boxes removed from Covanta by 12/23. In all, ten (10) 25 cubic yard roll-off bins for disposal were transported back to Tradebe.  Tradebe prefers to identify this shipment as an event, rather than an incident due to the fact that material was never "released!' in an uncontrolled fashion. Material was always under the control of knowledgeable personnel and inside facility structures designed for handling such materials.
column169: Although the delivery was accidental, Tradebe has identified several corrective actions to prevent a recurrence. Corrective actions already put in-place include:  1.) Require probation drivers (<90 days OT J) to only pick up trailers during normal dispatch business hours (days). 2.) Require probation drivers to confirm all load related information through the dispatcher before leaving with the load.  3.) Send daily e-mails to site supervisors detailing loads leaving during off-hours.  4.) Reaffirm "Stop Work" authority to questions discrepancies when noted.

column168: Driver was heading eastbound on Hwy 201 transporting a load to a nearby facility when trailer wondered to edge of the road and ditch in which driver was unable to maneuver trailer back onto highway. Truck a trailer went into the ditch and pup trailer rolled and separated from truck, crude oil started Leaking from the top hatch. Not sure if hatch was not properly secured or jared loose from crash. Approximately 5bbls had leaked out before driver could secure top hatch by tightening wing nuts. Driver then called field supervisor who in tum called local Sheriffs department. After Sheriff released Driver he drove truck back to Lunderby yard and trailer was pumped off by another truck and empty trailer haul to yard by Lunderby employees. Field Supervisor called LT Environmental out of Williston, ND who will be in charge of soil samples and testing. He then cleaned up spill hauled soil to Oaks Disposal in Lindsay, MT. We are waiting for the test results to come back and if there is no more clean up to be done reclamation of the site will start.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: GOOD TRANSPORTATION TANK TRUCK WAS AT THE INTERSECTION OF INDIANA 933 (LINCOLNWAY) HEADED WESTBOUND AWAITING TRAFFIC TO CLEAR TO BEGIN A LEFT HAND TURN TO SOUTHBOUND CHURCH STREET WHEN THE VEHICLE WAS STRUCK FROM BEHIND BY A FRONT DISCHARGE CEMENT MIXING TRUCK. IT WAS REPORTED THAT THE IMPACT CAUSED THE SEMI-TRAILER TO MOVE TO THE RIGHT. THE MIXER STRUCK THE TOP OF THE TANK TRUCK AT APPROXIMATELY THE TWO O'CLOCK POSITION OF THE TANK. (SEE ATTACHED PHOTOGRAPHS). PHOTOGRAPHS INDICATE THAT THE WELDED TANK HEAD AND SHELL REMAINED INTACT, BUT THE ALUMINUM RIPPED UNDER THE FORCE OF THE IMPACT. IT IS ASSUMED THAT THE DISCHARGE OF THE GASOLINE ONTO THE ASPHALT SURFACE OF THE ROADWAYS AND STORM DRAIN CATCH BASINS. THE MISHAWAKA FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND CONTAINED THE SPILLED/RELEASED GASOLINE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED SEVERAL BUSINESS DUE TO THE INCIDENT, BUT DID NOT HAVE ANY DOCUMENTATION AS TO HOW MANY.
column169: THIS INCIDENT INDICATES THAT THE DESIGN OF THE FRONT DISCHARGE CEMENT MIXER MAY NEED TO BE EXAMINED FURTHER TO PREVENT A SIMILAR INCIDENT. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THE DISCHARGE CHUTE AND WORKER PLATFORM EXTEND AHEAD OF THE FRONT BUMPER OF THE VEHICLE, THEREFORE MAKING THE BUMPER LESS THAN EFFECTIVE. THE STRONG STEEL USED IN THE CEMENT MIXER IS MICH STRONGER THAN THE ALUMINUM ALLOY USED IN THE TANK TRUCK.  THE CEMENT MIXER HAD BEEN REMOVED PRIOR TO OUR ARRIVAL AND THE EXACT POSITION OF THE CHUTE IS UNKNOWN. FROM PHOTOGRAPHS TAKEN SHORTLY AFTER THE ACCIDENT, IT APPEARS THAT THE CHUTE WAS SWUNG OVER TO THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE MIXER. IT APPEARS FROM THE PHOTOGRAPHS THAT THE PLATFORM OF THE MIXER HAD CONTACT WITH THE ALUMINUM TANK TRUCK.

column168: Micro nutrients driver of a “Yard Dog”, failed to properly set and verify the brakes were engaged when he parked to unload etch material. While unloading etch the Yard Dog with attached tanker of etch pulled away from piping connection.  As a result there was approximately 1,000 gallons of etch released in the back lot. The incident was reportable spill and IDEM, Marion County Health Department and Local Emergency Planning Committee were notified.
column169: Training was conducted to all drivers.  The driver that caused the incident was given a safety ticket and penalized on his bonus paycheck.  Safety ticket with this caompany you are penalized.    The truck and tanker will be chalked and enure brakes are engaged.

column168: Original comments:  Package was left by morning QA. Once I got to the package I put on protective gloves and checked for bar-code and OP-900 so I could print an MSDS. I put the package in a hazmat bin and brought it to the hazmat cage. One of the paint cans is missing the clip and is bent which caused the leak. Because it is paint, all other items were stained. Bin with the package was placed on the flammable liquid pallet in our hazmat cage.  New Comments:

Original comments:  This hazmat has been sitting in damages for over a month and I am not sure how it got damaged, but I assume that it had something to do with the fact it was sent over the top according to f track.  New Comments:

THE DRIVER OVERFILLED HIS CARGO TANK WHILE LOADING. UPON OBSERVATION OF THE SPILL THE DRIVER SHUT OFF THE PUMP AND STOPPED LOADING THE PROCESS. A VACUUM TRUCK RECOVERED AS MUCH OF THE OIL AS POSSIBLE. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND REMEDIATED AS PER KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT REQUIREMENTS.
column169: THE EMPLOYEE WAS DISCIPLINED WITH TIME OFF AND HAD MONETARY DEDUCTIONS FROM HIS INCENTIVE COMPENSATION AND SAFETY AWARD.

column168: DRIVER WAS EN ROUTE TO DELIVER PRODUCT TO SPEEDWAY 979 N. MAIN ST. IN NICHOLASVILLE, KY. HE WAS TURNING LEFT FROM THE RIGHT LANE OF US27 LEXINGTON ROAD ON AN OFF-CAMBER CORNER ONTO 27 BUSINESS MAIN ST., NICHOLASVILLE, KY. DURING THE TURN SAID HIS FOOT SLID OFF THE BRAKE AND ONTO THE GAS PEDAL ACCELERATING THE TRUCK AND CAUSING IT TO OVERTURN. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO EXIT THE TRUCK. NICHOLASVILLE EMT, POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES FROM NICHOLASVILLE WERE CALLED AND RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT WHERE THEY WERE ABLE TO STOP FLOW AND REMEDIATE THE AREA. THE OVERTURNED TRAILER WAS TREATED WITH PETRO-CLEAN FOAM BY THE BLUEGRASS AIRPORT FIRE DEPARTMENT. TWO ROTATOR RECOVERY UNITS WERE BROUGHT IN FROM ROBERTS HEAVY DUTY TOWING TO UPRIGHT THE UNITS.
column169: INCIDENT WILL BE DISCUSSED AT COMPANY SAFETY MEETINGS. SPEED AND TURNING COUNTERMEASURES WILL ALSO BE DISCUSSED.

column168: AT 1645 ON 12 DECEMBER 2018, KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY'S (KCS) ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED THAT INTERMODAL TRAILER JBHU 245706 WAS LEAKING A HAZMAT SUBSTANCE (CLASS 9, UN3082) FROM THE LEFT SIDE NEAR THE FRONT OF THE CONTAINER, AT THE KCS LAREDO, TX RAIL YARD. KCS MOBILIZED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED HAZMAT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND RESPOND. UPON ARRIVAL, THE CONTRACTOR VERIFIED A LIQUID RELEASE FROM THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. AFTER DONNING PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, THE CONTRACTOR FURTHER INVESTIGATED THE LOAD AND FOUND A DAMAGED 55 GALLON DRUM LEAKING AT THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. IN ORDER TO GAIN ACCESS, DRUMS BLOCKING ACCESS TO THE LEAKING DRUM WERE REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVER PACKED INTO A SECURE CONTAINER. THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS DECONTAMINATED, AND SPILLED MATERIAL OUTSIDE THE CONTAINER WAS COLLECTED AND CONTAINERIZED. ALL DRUMS WERE PLACED BACK ON THE TRAILER AND SECURED FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.

column168: ON 1210/2018 AT 6:19PM, KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY'S (KCS) ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED THAT HAZMAT TANK CAR UTLX 660625 (CLASS 9, UN3082) WAS LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY AT THE KCS LAREDO, TX RAIL YARD. KCS MOBILIZED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED HAZMAT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND RESPOND. UPON ARRIVAL, THE CONTRACTOR FOUND 8 OF 8 MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS TO BE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT (6 OF 8 SWING BOLTS WERE NOT IN POSITION). AFTER OPENING THE MANWAY, THE MANWAY NOZZLE GASKET WAS FOUND TO BE MISSING. A NEW NOZZLE GASKET WAS INSTALLED TO ENSURE A PROPER SEAL, THE MANWAY WAS  CLOSED, AND THE BOLTS TIGHTENED TOOL TIGHT. ALL OTHER CLOSURES WERE CHECKED AND FOUND SECURE. THE OUTSIDE OF THE CAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY DECONTAMINATED BEFORE THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION. FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD. column168: THE CFI TRACTOR/TRAILER UNIT FAILED TO MAKE THE UTRN AT THE "T" INTERSECTION AND CONTINUED ON STRAIGHT THROUGH THE INTERSECTION INTO A SOIL WATER DRAINAGE AREA LEADING OFF OF I-40. THE TRUCK CONTINUED DOWN THE SOIL DRAINAGE AREA A MEASURABLE DISTANCE UNTIL IT CAME TO REST IN THE DRY GRANULAR SOIL. AS A RESULT OF THE TRACTOR/TRAILER LEAVING THE ROADWAY THE CARGO (BATTERIES ON PALLETS) SHIFTED FORWARD AGAINST THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER ULTIMATELY CAUSING THE BATTERIES TO SHIFT OFF OF THE PALLETS AND ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  NO DIESEL OF ENGING FLUIDS WERE RELEASED. VERY LITTLE BATTERY ACID WAS RELEASED TO THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER.
column169: ATTENTIVE DRIVING, PRE-PLANNING ROUTES AND KNOWING WHERE TO UP COMING TURNS IN THE ROADS AREA LOCATED ON THE ROUTE.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTO AN UNDERGROUND TANK AT A GAS STATION. THE DRIVER HAD TO MOVE TRUCK AHEAD TO REACH NEXT UNDERGROUND TANK. DRIVER DID NOT UNHOOK HOSE FROM TRAILER BEFORE MOVING TRUCK. AS HE MOVED AHEAD, THE HOSE PULLED THE UNLOADING PIPE FROM THE DISCHARGE VALVE RESULTING IN A SPILL. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CLOSE THE EMERGENCY VALVE, STOPPING THE LEAK. THE ORIGINAL REPORT WAS 100 GALLONS, BUT AFTER REPAIRS WERE MADE AND FINISHED UNLOADING, THE CALCULATIONS SHOWED ONLY 30 GALLONS. ALL GAS WAS SPILLED ON CONCRETE AND CONTAINED TO LOCATION. FLOOR DRY WAS APPLIED TO SPILL TO ABSORB PRODUCT. CHS SWEPT UP CONTAMINATED FLOOR DRY TO BE DISPOSED OF.
column169: DRIVER INVOLVED WAS NOT FOLLOWING PROPER PROCEDURES. WE WILL GIVE THE DRIVER RETRAINING COURSE ON USING PROPER PROCEDURES. THE INCIDENT WILL ALSO BE REVIEWED WITH ALL COMPANY DRIVERS AT SAFETY MEETINGS.
